  <compounddef id="classmultifile_21" kind="predicate" language="Prolog" prot="public">
    <compoundname>multifile/1</compoundname>
    <briefdescription>
<para><bold>multifile</bold>( <emphasis>P</emphasis> ) </para>
    </briefdescription>
    <detaileddescription>
<para>defined in the <emphasis>ISO</emphasis> standard</para>
<para>Declares that a predicate or several predicates may be defined throughout several files <emphasis>P</emphasis> is a collection of one or more predicate indicators:</para>
<para><programlisting><codeline><highlight class="normal">:-<sp/></highlight><highlight class="keyword">multifile</highlight><highlight class="normal"><sp/>@</highlight><highlight class="stringliteral"></highlight><highlight class="normal"><sp/></highlight><highlight class="stringliteral"></highlight><highlight class="normal">user:portray_message/2<sp/>,<sp/></highlight><highlight class="keyword">multifile</highlight><highlight class="normal"><sp/>@</highlight><highlight class="stringliteral"></highlight><highlight class="normal"><sp/></highlight><highlight class="stringliteral"></highlight><highlight class="normal">user:message_hook/3<sp/></highlight><highlight class="keyword">.</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para>Instructs the compiler about the declaration of a predicate <emphasis>P</emphasis> in more than one file It must appear in the first of the loaded files where the predicate is declared, and before declaration of any of its clauses</para>
<para>Multifile declarations must be supported by <ref refid="classreconsult_21" kindref="compound">reconsult/1</ref> and <ref refid="classcompile_21" kindref="compound">compile/1</ref> : when a multifile predicate is reconsulted, only the clauses from the same file are removed</para>
<para>Since YAP4.3.0 multifile procedures can be static or dynamic</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem></listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
